---
import { SITE_TITLE } from "../config/site";
import SiteLayout from '../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';
---

<SiteLayout
  title={`${SITE_TITLE} Instructions`}
  description="A plain-language guide to using ban.gs."
  currentPath="/instructions"
>
  <div class="grid gap-4 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,0.72fr)_minmax(0,1fr)]">
    <aside class="card h-fit p-5 sm:p-6">
      <p class="text-xs font-700 uppercase tracking-[0.24em] text-primary-700">Quick summary</p>
      <h1
        class="mt-2 font-display text-[2.4rem] font-800 leading-tight tracking-[-0.04em] text-text sm:text-[2.8rem]"
      >
        Instructions
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-text-secondary">
        A simple setup guide for turning your browser’s search bar into a fast shortcut router.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-4 grid gap-3">
        <div class="rounded-[20px] bg-bg-soft p-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-700 text-text">No extension required</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-text-secondary">
            Most browsers support custom search engines natively. <a href="https://helium.computer" target="_blank">Some browsers</a> even have native !bangs support.</a>
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-[20px] bg-bg-soft p-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-700 text-text">One install link</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-text-secondary">
            <code>?q=%s</code> is the part your browser needs.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-[20px] bg-bg-soft p-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-700 text-text">Still flexible</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-text-secondary">
            You can change defaults, lucky mode, and add custom shortcuts later.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <div class="grid gap-4">
      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-3">1. Try it on the home page</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-3">
          Use the search bar on the front page and type something like:
        </p>
        <div class="grid gap-2 text-sm">
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2 font-mono">!gh react</div>
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2 font-mono">!w solar system</div>
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2 font-mono">
            best noise cancelling headphones
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-3">2. Learn the basic rule</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          If your search starts with a bang like <code>!gh</code> or
          <code>!w</code>, bangs.to sends you to that site. If your search has no bang, it goes to
          your default search engine.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-3">3. Set it as your browser search engine</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-3">
          Open Settings on the home page and copy the install link. It will look like <code
            >https://bangs.to/?q=%s</code
          >. That link tells your browser where to send anything you type in the address bar.
        </p>

        <div
          class="rounded-[22px] border border-primary-100 bg-primary-50/75 px-4 py-4 text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4"
        >
          You only need one piece of information:
          <br />
          <code class="text-text">Search URL:</code>
          <code>https://bangs.to/?q=%s</code>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-700 mb-2 text-text">Chrome, Arc, Brave, and Edge</h3>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-3">
          Open your browser settings and search for <strong>Search engines</strong>. Then add a new
          search engine.
        </p>
        <div class="grid gap-2 text-sm mb-4">
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2">
            <strong>Name:</strong> bangs.to
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2">
            <strong>Shortcut:</strong> bangs.to
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2 font-mono">
            <strong class="font-sans not-italic">URL:</strong>
            https://bangs.to/?q=%s
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">
          Save it, then set it as your default search engine if you want normal address-bar searches
          to go through bangs.to automatically.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-700 mb-2 text-text">Firefox and Firefox-based browsers</h3>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-3">
          Visit the home page once first. Many Firefox-based browsers can detect the site
          automatically as a search engine. Then open browser settings, go to <strong>Search</strong
          >, and choose <strong>bangs.to</strong> from the list if it appears.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">
          If it does not appear automatically, you can still keep using the site directly from the
          home page, or add it manually using browser tools or extensions that support custom search
          engines.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-700 mb-2 text-text">Safari</h3>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">
          Safari is more limited with custom search engines than Chrome or Firefox. If Safari does
          not let you add it directly, the simplest option is to keep bangs.to open as a pinned tab or
          use a Safari extension that adds custom search engine support.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-700 mb-2 text-text">How to test that it worked</h3>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-3">
          Click into your browser’s address bar and type a search like these:
        </p>
        <div class="grid gap-2 text-sm mb-4">
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2 font-mono">!gh react</div>
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2 font-mono">!yt ambient mix</div>
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2 font-mono">weather vancouver</div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          If it is set up correctly, your browser should send you straight to GitHub, YouTube, or
          your default web search without needing to open the bangs.to home page first.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-3">4. Change your defaults if you want</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          Open Settings to pick your default search engine, choose where autocomplete suggestions
          come from, and decide how “Feeling Lucky” should behave.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-3">5. Add your own shortcuts</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          If there is a site you use often, open Settings and add a custom bang. For example, you
          could make <code>!docs</code> go to your team’s internal docs search.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-3">6. What happens behind the scenes?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          The short version is: your browser recognizes the query and sends you straight to the
          right place. You do not see an extra redirect page. That is why it feels fast.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2 class="section-title mb-3">7. If it does not work</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-3">Most setup problems come down to one of these:</p>
        <div class="grid gap-2 text-sm text-text-secondary">
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2">
            You pasted the wrong URL. Make sure it ends with <code>?q=%s</code>.
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2">
            Your browser did not make bangs.to the default search engine yet.
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2">
            A browser restart is needed before the new search engine shows up everywhere.
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-[18px] bg-bg-soft px-3 py-2">
            Safari may need an extension or workaround because it is stricter than other browsers.
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
